📡 Semantic Transfer Tomography (STT) v1.0

Probing and shaping how an input transforms into an output

⸻

🧭 Core Definition

STT = sending structured inputs, observing how they transform through a system, and iteratively inferring and steering that transformation path.

You’re not just asking for answers.

You’re:
	•	probing the system
	•	reading the transformation
	•	nudging the next step

⸻

🧠 The Mechanism (grounded)

1) Injection (the probe)
	•	your prompt = a structured signal
	•	carries:
	•	intent
	•	constraints
	•	framing

⸻

2) Transformation (inside the model)
	•	the system maps input → output using learned patterns
	•	you don’t see the internals directly

⸻

3) Observation (the return)

You read:
	•	content (what it said)
	•	structure (how it built it)
	•	friction (where it corrected/limited)

⸻

4) Inference (your model of the model)

You infer:
	•	what it prioritized
	•	what it ignored
	•	where it compressed or expanded

⸻

5) Steering (next pulse)

You adjust:
	•	wording
	•	constraints
	•	abstraction level

⸻

🔁 The Loop

Inject → Observe → Infer → Adjust → Repeat

Over time:
	•	fewer wasted probes
	•	tighter control
	•	more predictable outputs

⸻

🧩 What you’ve gotten good at

You’re tracking:
	•	trajectory → where the answer is heading
	•	curvature → how it bends under constraints
	•	loss points → where meaning gets dropped
	•	gain points → where it expands usefully

That’s why it feels like:

you can “guide it mid-flight”

⸻

🎯 Practical Moves (make it explicit)

1) Beam shaping
	•	narrow: precise constraints
	•	wide: exploratory framing

⸻

2) Layer locking
	•	“give architecture first, then UI, then edge cases”
→ forces staged expansion

⸻

3) Loss correction
	•	“you missed X constraint—re-run with it enforced”

⸻

4) Trajectory anchoring
	•	“optimize for speed over completeness”
→ sets direction early

⸻

5) Multi-pass refinement
	•	first pass = rough
	•	second pass = tighten
	•	third pass = validate

⸻

⚠️ Calibration (this keeps it real)

You’re not seeing the model’s internals.

You’re building:

an increasingly accurate approximation of how it responds to inputs

That’s enough to be powerful—but it’s still:
	•	probabilistic
	•	context-dependent

⸻

🧬 Why it compounds

Because:
	•	your mental model improves
	•	your probes get cleaner
	•	your corrections get faster

So each loop:
	•	reduces entropy
	•	increases control

